Logicals - recap

  • We already used arithmetic operators: +, -, *, /, ^. They return numeric data.
  • Logical operations are assertions and return logical values.
  • < less than
  • <= less than or equal to
  • > greater than
  • >= greater than or equal to
  • == equal to
  • != not equal to
  • !x not x
  • x|y x OR y
  • x&y x AND y
> 1 < 4  # we claim: 1 is less than 4
## [1] TRUE
> 
> 1 > 4  # we claim: 1 is greater than 4
## [1] FALSE
> 
> 1 == 4 # we claim: 1 is equal to 4
## [1] FALSE
> 
> 1 != 4 # we claim: 1 is not equal to 4
## [1] TRUE

Logicals - recap

  • We can also apply logical operations to vectors.
  • Like match() the returned object is a logical vector
> vx <- 1:7     # vector with 7 numbers
> 
> vx < 5        # we claim: an element is less than 5
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE
> 
> vx[vx == 3]   # return all elements that are exactly 3
## [1] 3
> 
> vx[vx != 3]   # return all elements that are not 3
## [1] 1 2 4 5 6 7
> 
> vx[(vx>1) & (vx<5)]   # return all elements that are greater 1 AND lower 5
## [1] 2 3 4
> 
> vx[(vx<3) | (vx>5)]   # return all elements that either lower 3 OR greater 5
## [1] 1 2 6 7

Data frame - recap

  • Similar to matrices

    • A data frame is a two-dimensional arrangement of objects with same number of columns per row

  • Similar to lists

    • Each column can be a different data type
    • All objects within one column must be of the same type
> vf <- c("apple","banana","strawberry","lemmon")
> vc <- c("green","yellow","red","yellow")
> df <- data.frame(fruit = vf, color = vc, taste = c("sweet","sweet","sweet","sour") )
> df$in.stock <- c(25,33,0,156)
> df
##        fruit  color taste in.stock
## 1      apple  green sweet       25
## 2     banana yellow sweet       33
## 3 strawberry    red sweet        0
## 4     lemmon yellow  sour      156

Data frame - manipulation

  • Nearly identical to matrices manipulation
> df$in.stock <- df$in.stock + 20    # we get a new delivery -> all fruits plus 20
> 
> rownames(df)  # set or get all column names of the df
## [1] "1" "2" "3" "4"
> 
> colnames(df)  # set or get all column names of the df
## [1] "fruit"    "color"    "taste"    "in.stock"
> 
> n <- colnames(df)
> colnames(df)[1] <- "vegetables"
> colnames(df)
## [1] "vegetables" "color"      "taste"      "in.stock"
> colnames(df) <- n
> 
> length(df)    # careful! It is the number of columns!
## [1] 4
> 
> dim(df)       # this returns a vector of both, row number and column number
## [1] 4 4
> 
> nrow(df)      # number of rows, like in dim(df)[1]
## [1] 4

Data frame - subset

  • Access data frame objects
    • Similar to matrices by using square brackets [ , ].
    • Similar to lists by using dollar sign $ notation
> df[1, ]                 # get first row
##   fruit color taste in.stock
## 1 apple green sweet       45
> df[, 1]                 # get first column
## [1] "apple"      "banana"     "strawberry" "lemmon"
> 
> df$color
## [1] "green"  "yellow" "red"    "yellow"
> df[, "color"]           # get column "color", same result: df$color
## [1] "green"  "yellow" "red"    "yellow"
> 
> df[c(2,3), ]            # get 2nd and 3rd row
##        fruit  color taste in.stock
## 2     banana yellow sweet       53
## 3 strawberry    red sweet       20
> 
> df$color == "yellow"    # find all yellow fruits
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
> 
> df[df$color == "yellow", ]
##    fruit  color taste in.stock
## 2 banana yellow sweet       53
## 4 lemmon yellow  sour      176

Factors - creation

  • A nominal (categorical) variable can be stored as a factor

  • The factor stores the nominal values as a vector of numbers

  • By the internal levels vector, these numbers are mapped to the original values

    • The levels vector is alphabetically sorted
    • Use the factor() function to create a factor to your needs
> df$color <- rep(c("red","blue"),nrow(df)/2)
> df$color
## [1] "red"  "blue" "red"  "blue"
> df$color <- as.factor(df$color)
> df$color
## [1] red  blue red  blue
## Levels: blue red
> 
> df$color <- factor(df$color , levels = c("blue","red"))
> df$color
## [1] red  blue red  blue
## Levels: blue red
> 
> levels(df$color)
## [1] "blue" "red"

Factors - creation

  • Factors can represent categories, important for statistics or graphics

Functions

You already learned a lot of basic functions on-the-fly

  • c(), rep()
  • str(), typeof()
  • length(), dim()
  • sort(), rev(), unique()
  • list(), matrix(), t(), data.frame()
  • as.double(), as.character(), sum()

The values that are given to functions are called arguments

You can write, save, and use your own functions. (not needed here)

> my_sum <- function(v){
+    sum(v) # local scope
+ }
> 
> v <- c(4,5,6) # global scope
> res <- my_sum(c(1,2,3))
> res
## [1] 6

Exercise 1

  • How many yellow fruits do we currently have in stock?
> vf <- c("apple","banana","kiwifruit","strawberry","orange","lemmon")
> vc <- c("green","yellow","brown","red","orange","yellow")
> df <- data.frame(fruit = vf, color = vc)
> df$in.stock <- c(25,40,33,0,12,156)

Solution:

> df[df$color == "yellow", ]                  # extract rows with yellow fruits
##    fruit  color in.stock
## 2 banana yellow       40
## 6 lemmon yellow      156
> 
> df[df$color == "yellow", "in.stock"]        # only display the column in.stock, note: it is a vector
## [1]  40 156
> 
> sum(df[df$color == "yellow", "in.stock"])   # sum-up the returned in.stock values
## [1] 196

Packages

  • R packages are collections of functions and data sets developed by the community.

  • Packages increase the power of R by improving existing base R functionalities, or by adding new ones.

  • Large collections (repositories) of packages are CRAN and Bioconductor.

  • The methods to install packages from there slightly differ, so here are both commands:

DO NOT RUN NOW!

> # CRAN package installation command
> install.packages(c("pheatmap","ggplot2","tidyr","readxl"))
> 
> # Bioconductor package installation command
> install.packages("BiocManager")
> BiocManager::install("DESeq2")

The DEG data set in deg.df

  • Gene expression analysis using RNA-seq in the worm C. elegans (see columns id & symbol)
  • 6 biological replicates: 3 controls / 3 with knock-out of a target gene (control_ & ko_)
  • Differential expression statistics with DESeq2 (log2FoldChange & padj)
  • Interpretation: log2FoldChange > 0 up-regulation in KO | log2FoldChange < 0 down-reg. in KO

Exercise 2

  1. How many genes are significantly differentially expressed, i.e. do have a padj smaller or equals 5?

    • Take care of NA values via is.na() function!

  2. For significantly differentially expressed genes, do a boxplot of the normalized read counts for samples control_1 and ko_1.

    • For a better scale, log transform the expression values.

Exercise 2 - Solution

> na.df <- deg.df[! is.na(deg.df$padj) , ]
> sig <- na.df$padj <= 0.05
> sig.n <- sum(sig)
> 
> sig.df <- data.frame(
+   reads=c(na.df$control_1[sig],na.df$ko_1[sig]), 
+   sample=c(rep("control_1",sig.n),rep("ko_1",sig.n))
+ )
> 
> sig.df$reads = log2(sig.df$reads)
> 
> head(sig.df, n=4)
##       reads    sample
## 1 10.560123 control_1
## 2 10.975161 control_1
## 3  7.731073 control_1
## 4  8.892880 control_1
> 
> tail(sig.df, n=4)
##          reads sample
## 4945  6.290250   ko_1
## 4946  7.541382   ko_1
## 4947  7.833990   ko_1
## 4948 11.006236   ko_1
> boxplot(reads~sample,sig.df)

Exercise 2 - Solution

> log2(na.df[1,3:8])
##   control_1 control_2 control_3     ko_1     ko_2     ko_3
## 1  11.91309  11.81861   11.9443 12.05713 11.97386 11.93261
> library("tidyr")
> sig.df <- pivot_longer(log2(na.df[sig,3:8]), cols= 1:6, names_to = "sample", values_to = "reads")
> boxplot(reads~sample,sig.df)

The graphics package ggplot2

  • ggplot2 is a system for programmatically creating graphics, based on “The Grammar of Graphics”.

  • To operate, it requires

    • A full data frame
    • An aesthetics which defines how to map data frame columns to axes
    • The graphical primitives to use
ggplot(dataframe, aes()) + geom_point()


Load the package into the session:

> library("ggplot2")

Documentation: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/index.html

Cheat sheet: https://github.com/rstudio/cheatsheets/blob/master/data-visualization-2.1.pdf

Scatter plot

Inspect the correlation of expression values between two samples.

> ggplot(deg.df, aes(x = log10(control_1), y = log10(ko_2))) + geom_point(alpha = 0.1)

Volcano plot

A volcano plot displays the relation of expression strength (log2FoldChange) and significance (padj)

> # calculate the y-axis data
> deg.df$negLogPval <- (-log10(deg.df$padj))
> 
> ggplot(deg.df, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = negLogPval)) + geom_point()

Faceting - divide a plot into subplots

Pretty Violin plot

We can highly customize our plots in ggplot2. It needs some practice. Again, the cheat sheets helps a lot to discover the possibilities.

p <- ggplot(ddl.sel, aes(id, reads, fill=group))+
  geom_violin(scale = "width")+
  labs(title = "RNA-seq Gene Expression",
       subtitle = "of very important genes",
       x = "Gene (WormBase ID)",
       y = "Number of normalized reads",
       fill = "Treatment group") +
  ylim(0,15000)+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#56B4E9","#E69F00"))+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Pretty box plot

#install.packages("ggpubr")
library("ggpubr") # install unless available

p <- ggplot(ddl.sel, aes(id, reads, fill=group))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title = "RNA-seq Gene Expression",
       subtitle = "of very important genes",
       x = "Gene (WormBase ID)",
       y = "Number of normalized reads",
       fill = "Treatment group") +
  ylim(0,17000)+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#56B4E9","#E69F00"))+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")+
  stat_compare_means(comparisons = list( 
    c("WBGene00000001","WBGene00000123"), 
    c("WBGene00000123","WBGene00007605")), 
    label = "p.signif", 
    label.y = c(15000, 16000), 
    method = "wilcox.test", paired=F)

Storing figures as PDF

Simple graphics

By surrounding the barplot() function by pdf() and dev.off() the figure is sent to a PDF file and not to the screen.

> # store the figure in a pdf file
> pdf(file="animals_barplot.pdf")  # open the pdf
> 
> barplot(animals$size, names.arg=animals$animal, main="Animal properties", ylab="Size (cm)")
> 
> dev.off()                        # close the pdf
## png 
##   2

Storing figures as PDF

ggplot2

ggplot2 has an own export function called ggsave(), the second argument is the plot itself.

> p <- ggplot(ddl.sel, aes(group, reads, fill=group)) + geom_boxplot() + facet_wrap(~id)
> ggsave(filename = "export_boxplot.facet.pdf",  p)
